-I discussed the possible causes of sleep disordered breathing including blocked or narrowed airways in the nose, mouth, or throat, or blockage caused by relaxed throat muscles and tongue.
-I discussed the treatment of sleep apnea including lifestyle changes, breathing/dental devices, and CPAP.

HPI Notes: 75-year-old female former smoker (quit 30 years ago, 28 pack years) with past medical history of hypertension, major depressive disorder, HLD, RLS, GERD s/p fundoplication, osteoarthritis who presents to establish care for concern for interstitial lung disease. She reports having voice that would just stop. She went to speech therapy without improvement. She has been evaluated by ENT (Dr. Yee and McLaughlin). She has been taking dexilant in the AM and Famotidine in the PM. This chronic cough began 2 years ago. She reports in 2021-08-17 she started to have shortness of breath and exhaustion. She has lost endurance in the last year. Patient denies fevers/chills, night sweats, weight loss, and hemoptysis. Patient denies sinus pressure/headache, itchy/red eyes, sore throat. She reports nasal congestion/drainage, and post-nasal drip. She has sinus surgery x 3. She reports occasional sneezing fits. She has 2 dogs and 4 foster dogs. All are short hair dogs. She does not have carpets at home. SHe reports cough is regardless of location. She wakes up in middle of the night coughing. Patient reports choking, gagging, snoring. She denies falling asleep in public places, witnessed apneas, AM headaches, daytime fatigue, or daytime napping. She has been diagnosed with sleep apnea in the past and she was on CPAP in the past. She reports having dry mouth. She had difficulty since she was unable to move about the bed like she usually does, and with dry mouth. She said a following study was done and showed no sleep apnea. She reports multiple bouts of bronchitis as a child. She is up-to-date with her influenza, pneumococcal, COVID vaccines. Myocardial perfusion scan (2021-12-21): Normal pharmacological stress test and rest myocardial perfusion scan by qualitative and quantitative analysis with no new perfusion defects compared to 2014-09-17. CT chest (2021-12-16): Mild emphysematous change with bullae formation in the right upper lobe consistent with COPD. Interstitial fibrosis in the periphery of the lungs greatest at the lung bases where there is mild traction bronchiectasis. No definite air trapping. 5 mm right upper lobe pulmonary nodule. No lymphadenopathy. Moderate hiatal hernia. Perinephric stranding. PFTs (2021-12-07): No demonstrable obstructive lung disease. Bronchodilator testing not done. No evidence of restrictive physiology. Mild diffusion limitation with DLCO of 16.5 (61%) . Labs (2021-09-02): H/H: 11.3/36.4. Absolute eosinophil 0.1. HC 03: 28. Creatinine 0.8. AST/ALT: 27/24. NT proBNP of 94. ESR and CRP Negative. RF: <5. ANA negative. She worked as an executive assistance within in legislature. Patient denies exposures to dust, silica, foundries, factories, birds/pigeons, hot tubs, TB, asbestos.

HPI Notes: Mrs. Johnstons is a 75 y/o female with history of OSA, bronchiectasis, GERD, allergic rhinitis, and obesity who presents to discuss results of PSG. She was last seen as a new patient by Dr. Grewal on 2022-01-03. Patient was on CPAP for a few years in the past, last time 5-10 years ago. Patient says she tried many many masks and had best results with nasal pillows. Patient also used oral appliance in the past, years ago.

HPI Notes: Ms. Johnston is a 76 YO female with PMH of OSA, GERD, bronchiectasis, and allergic rhinitis presents for a follow up. She was last seen on 2022-02-17 by Dawn. Split night sleep study (2022-01-20)- Moderate to severe OSA with AHI of 25.7/hr and minimum oxygen saturation was 81%. CPAP compliance from 2022-03-24-2022-04-22 shows 15 out of 30 days used with average use of 7 hours and 14 as an AHI of 0.6. Patient was on a vacation and he was traveling machine for the rest of the days. States from respiratory standpoint, she is at her baseline. Reports dyspnea on exertion. Denies cough and mucous. Denies fever, chills, and night sweats.

HPI Notes: Due to COVID-19 outbreak, today's visit was conducted via telehealth. Ms. Johnston is a 76 YO female with PMH of OSA, GERD, bronchiectasis, and allergic rhinitis presents for a follow up. States she is struggling with mask seal due to side sleeping. Reports nose dryness after taking mask off in the morning. Split night sleep study (2022-01-20)- Moderate to severe OSA with AHI of 25.7/hr and minimum oxygen saturation was 81%. CPAP compliance from 2022-04-06-2022-06-04 shows 52/60 days use with average use of 6 hours and 43 mins and AHI of 1.1. States from respiratory standpoint, she is at her baseline. Reports dyspnea on exertion. States she is still coughing but it is not as much as it was before. Denies fever, chills, and night sweats.

HPI Notes: Ms. Johnston is a 76 YO female with PMH of OSA, GERD, bronchiectasis, and allergic rhinitis presents for a follow up. Pt. states she has not been able to get restful sleep with CPAP. She is scheduled for Inspire implant surgery on 2023-01-08 with Dr. Scott Fuller through UC Davis. Split night sleep study (2022-01-20)- Moderate to severe OSA with AHI of 25.7/hr and minimum oxygen saturation was 81%. CPAP compliance from 2022-10-04-2023-01-01 shows 42/90 days use with average use of 4 hours and 23 mins and AHI of 1.6. States from respiratory standpoint, she is at her baseline. Reports dyspnea on exertion. States she is still coughing but it is not as much as it was before. Denies fever, chills, and night sweats. PFT (2021)- spirometry and available lung volume data indicate near normal physiology. Isolated reduction in diffusion capacity.
